body:
I have a solution, but it doesn't allow overriding previous escape setting. 
e.g. once cached `select('name', false)` will then not be overridden 
by a new, later, un-cached `select('name',true)`.

@uicestone your example includes protected methods, here is an updated version,
(which i used in my tests) that uses get_compiled_select() and reset_query() instead:

``` php
$this->db->start_cache();
  $this->db->select('name', false);
  $this->db->from('people');
  $this->db->where('success >', 20); // escaped
$this->db->stop_cache();

$this->db->select('name', true); // won't be added
$this->db->select('phone', false);
var_dump( $this->db->get_compiled_select() );

// $this->db->reset_query(); // already done by compiled_select

$this->db->select('address', false);
$this->db->or_where('success < ', 10, false); // not escaped
var_dump( $this->db->get_compiled_select() );

$this->db->flush_cache();
```

